fields.title: Flipped
fields.review: At times, the movie feels like a commercial for Wonder Bread, stretched to feature length.

fields.title: Mamma Mia!
fields.review: It's impossible not to go along with the feeling when such a strangely life-affirming song as Dancing Queen is blasted in your ears.

fields.title: Ghostbusters
fields.review: Part of the sheer joy of this movie -- aside from the comic timing of Bill Murray -- is the cartoonish crapness of its apparitions and their placid acceptance by the Ghostbusters team.

fields.title: Ghostbusters II
fields.review: The sequel is, on the whole, a fairly mechanical spook show, filled with grinning ghosts that are definitely ghoulish but hardly menacing.

fields.title: Thor
fields.review: Thor is on much safer ground here on Earth. The tone is immediately different: more relaxed; comic, not cosmic.

fields.title: Thor: The Dark World
fields.review: Comic-book superheroes have become so angst-ridden in recent years it's a relief to be around one who has hung on to his sense of humour.

fields.title: Thor: Ragnarok
fields.review: Beautifully filmed with serious kinetic energy by director Taika Waititi, with a crackling script, Thor: Ragnarok is a heap of fun. Cue 'Immigrant Song!'

fields.title: Thor: Love and Thunder
fields.review: It brings up a lot of interesting ideas and ultimately does almost nothing with them.

fields.title: Free Guy
fields.review: Free Guy is a very knowing movie, but part of its knowingness is its pop lightness -- even its blandness, if that can be seen as a virtue.

fields.title: The Adam Project
fields.review: A science fiction adventure with lots of humor.
